## A. Exposure Summary

Our aerospace division has contracted to deliver a major component assembly to a European client, generating a **EUR 16,987,302 receivable due in 12 months**. Because our reporting currency is USD, this creates a meaningful foreign exchange exposure: every 1-cent move in the EURUSD rate produces approximately **$169,873 in gain or loss** on the receivable.

As a U.S. exporter receiving Euros, we are naturally **long EUR**. The primary risk is EUR depreciation relative to the USD — if the euro weakens, our USD proceeds fall below plan. Conversely, EUR appreciation would increase proceeds, representing upside optionality. The hedging decision centers on the cost-benefit trade-off between locking in certainty (forward/money market) and preserving upside potential (put option).

