## B. Summary of Hedge Outcomes

The table below presents USD proceeds under each strategy. The forward hedge provides the certainty benchmark. The money market hedge replicates the forward synthetically via the borrow-convert-invest mechanism; under Covered Interest Parity (CIP), it should converge to the forward result. The divergence observed in Stage 2 reflects the wide gap between the spot rate entered (1.7650) and the forward rate (1.0935) — a data anomaly flagged for correction before CFO presentation. The put option establishes a USD floor while retaining upside if the EUR appreciates.

| Strategy | USD Proceeds | Certainty | Key Trade-Off |
|---|---|---|---|
| **1. Forward Hedge** | $18,575,615 | Full — locked-in rate | No upside participation if EUR rises |
| **2. Money Market Hedge** | $29,848,366 `*` | Full — locked-in via borrow/invest | Liquidity draw; balance sheet impact; CIP anomaly flagged |
| **3. Put Option Hedge** | ~$22,274,939 (floor) | Partial — floor with upside | Premium cost of $322,759; upside retained above `K_put` |
| **4. Call Option (Reference)** | Variable — no floor | None — downside fully exposed | Not appropriate as primary hedge for exporter |
| **5. No Hedge** | Variable (`S_T × FC_AMT`) | None — fully exposed | Maximum risk; budget unpredictability |

> `*` The Stage 2 money market result of $29,848,366 reflects a spot input of 1.7650 inconsistent with the 1.0935 forward rate. Under correct CIP, money market proceeds should approximate the forward result of **$18,575,615**. This discrepancy should be corrected by aligning `S0` with the current implied spot prior to final CFO presentation.

