## C. Sensitivity Analysis & Scenario Interpretation

The Stage 2 sensitivity table evaluates USD proceeds as the EUR/USD spot rate at maturity (`S_T`) varies from 1.40 to 1.52. Extrapolating the underlying logic to the ±5% range around the 1.0935 forward (approximately 1.038 to 1.148), the following patterns emerge:

### EUR Depreciation Scenarios (`S_T` < 1.0935)

When the euro weakens at maturity, the unhedged exporter suffers a direct reduction in USD proceeds — approximately **$169,873 per $0.01 decline** in `S_T`. The forward hedge fully insulates against this loss; proceeds remain locked at $18,575,615. The put option similarly provides a floor: once `S_T` falls below `K_put`, the put is exercised and floor proceeds are guaranteed net of the $322,759 premium. No hedge is the worst outcome in depreciation scenarios, exposing the full downside.

### EUR Appreciation Scenarios (`S_T` > 1.0935)

When the euro strengthens above the forward rate, the unhedged position and the put option holder both benefit. The put holder lets the option expire worthless and converts at the higher spot (net of the sunk premium). The forward hedge, by contrast, **sacrifices this upside entirely** — the company is obligated to sell EUR at 1.0935 even if the market has moved to 1.15 or higher. This opportunity cost is the defining trade-off of the forward.

| Scenario | Forward Hedge | Put Option Hedge | No Hedge |
|---|---|---|---|
| **EUR Depreciates** (`S_T` < `F0`) | ✅ Protected — proceeds locked | ✅ Protected — put exercised, floor applies | ❌ Fully exposed — proceeds decline |
| **EUR at Parity** (`S_T` = `F0`) | Neutral — same as market | Break-even (premium drag only) | Same as forward result |
| **EUR Appreciates** (`S_T` > `F0`) | ❌ Opportunity cost — locked below market | ✅ Upside retained (net of premium) | ✅ Upside captured fully |

